<section class="hero">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="hero-kicker">Features</p>
    <h1>Ten capabilities. One unified instrument.</h1>
    <p class="hero-lede">
      Sirius Looper isn't a feature list bolted onto a recorder. It is a
      complete production environment from physical input to physical
      output — input mixer, always-running tape, output mixer, parallel
      direct layer — built on the decision that musical time is a
      concept, not a number, until the very last moment.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="feature-list">

      <article class="feature">
        <p class="feature-tag">01 · Signature</p>
        <h3>Retroactive Capture</h3>
        <p>
          The <span class="term">tape</span> runs from the moment the
          session opens. <span class="term">Mark In</span> stamps a
          start at the playhead; <span class="term">Mark Out</span>
          closes the region and auto-promotes it into the song. The
          in-point can then move backward to catch the pickup note you
          didn't have time to mark. The idea, not the reflex, drives
          the capture.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="feature">
        <p class="feature-tag">02 · New</p>
        <h3>Input Mixer → Tape → Output Mixer</h3>
        <p>
          The signal path is a full creative mixer on each side of the
          always-running tape, with the tape as the pivot. Both mixers
          are <span class="term">modality-agnostic</span> — live audio,
          live MIDI, live video, and file I/O are first-class signal
          types in the same channel architecture. Per channel, you
          choose whether processing is committed to tape or recorded as
          recoverable metadata. There is no separate mixer app and no
          render-vs-playback distinction.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="feature">
        <p class="feature-tag">03 · New</p>
        <h3>The Direct Layer</h3>
        <p>
          A parallel signal path from input mixer to output mixer that
          bypasses the tape entirely. Sub-millisecond live monitoring
          for vocal reinforcement, guitar amps, and any source where
          even a few buffers of latency would be unacceptable. Carries
          signal, not time-anchored data — so the tape stays the single
          source of truth.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="feature">
        <p class="feature-tag">04</p>
        <h3>Phrase-Based Arrangement</h3>
        <p>
          A <span class="term">Phrase</span> is a complete musical
          utterance — a verse, a chorus, a fill. <span class="term">Loops</span>
          are mechanisms inside phrases, not the unit of thought. A
          single phrase may contain multiple loops in different time
          domains, one-shot content, or silence — whatever the music
          actually demands.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="feature">
        <p class="feature-tag">05</p>
        <h3>Polymetric Phrases</h3>
        <p>
          A 4/4 drum loop and a 7/8 ostinato coexist inside a single
          phrase without approximation. Each carries its own meter; they
          only need to agree at phrase boundaries. Polyrhythms,
          cross-meters, and unequal cycles are not edge cases — they are
          first-class citizens of the data model.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="feature">
        <p class="feature-tag">06</p>
        <h3>Exact Micro-Timing</h3>
        <p>
          Swing, pocket, deliberate drag — all captured at the
          substrate's full precision. Sirius never quantizes a
          performance to a grid. The instant quantization touches a
          performance, the feel dies; the architecture exists to make
          that impossible.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="feature">
        <p class="feature-tag">07</p>
        <h3>Lossless Multi-Take</h3>
        <p>
          Every attempt, every edit, every rejected idea is preserved
          on tape. Destructive cleanup is available later, but nothing
          captured during the session is thrown away in the moment.
          The take you wished you had kept is still there.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="feature">
        <p class="feature-tag">08</p>
        <h3>Role-Based Improvisation</h3>
        <p>
          A phrase declares its role — verse, chorus, bridge — and at
          performance time, the same slot can be filled by different
          phrases of the same role. Structured improvisation inside a
          fixed arrangement, without rebuilding the song every night.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="feature">
        <p class="feature-tag">09</p>
        <h3>Recursive Arrangement</h3>
        <p>
          <span class="term">Sets → Songs → Sections → Phrases → Loops</span>.
          The same data model at every level. Arrangement happens at
          the phrase level and above; the levels nest cleanly because
          they share a single set of operations.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="feature">
        <p class="feature-tag">10</p>
        <h3>Plugin Hosting &amp; MIDI 2.0</h3>
        <p>
          Sirius is a standalone host for third-party effects in
          <span class="term">CLAP</span>, <span class="term">VST3</span>,
          and <span class="term">AU</span> formats. Plugins run
          <span class="term">out-of-process</span> so a crashing
          third-party plugin can never take the session with it. The
          MIDI side is full <span class="term">MIDI 2.0 / UMP</span>:
          per-note pitch bend, per-note pressure, MPE, and 32-bit
          controllers are stored on tape exactly as received and
          reproduced exactly on playback.
        </p>
      </article>

    </div>
  </div>
</section>

